1. Docker Command Structure

      Modern Structure:  docker <management command> <sub command> [options]
          example: docker container run container_name
      
      Old Structure:  docker <command> (options)
          example: docker run container_name


2. Docker System Commands

      docker version — Check installation details (client/server).
      
      docker system df — Shows Docker disk usage.
      
      docker system prune — Removes unused containers, networks, and volumes.
      
      docker image prune -a — Deletes all unused images.


3. Docker Configuration

      docker login — Authenticate with Docker Hub or other registries.
      
      docker logout — Logout (recommended for security).

4. Container Management

      docker container ls — List running containers.
      
      docker container ls -a — List all containers (including stopped ones).
      
      docker container rm <id> — Remove container(s).
      
      docker container rm -f <id> — Force remove running container.

5. Inspecting Containers

      docker container exec -it <container> bash — Access container shell.
      
      docker container logs <container> — Show logs.
      
      docker container top <container> — Show processes.
      
      docker container stats — Live resource usage.
      
      docker container inspect <container> — Configuration details.






